# 04 · Visual Language

*What the mood board says, decoded. Your board isn't a single aesthetic — it's a tension. And that tension IS the brand.*

| From the Board | Brand Translation |
| --- | --- |
| Golden honey drips · Swirling soft-serve · Amber pours · Food in motion | The drizzle is always the hero. Every shot features motion — food alive on the pour. |
| Surreal collage · Tiny figures on food · Miniature skaters on cream · PB&J macro | Earned permission to be playful and surreal. Food as landscape. Scale is a creative tool. |
| 70s arched interiors · Burnt orange · Groovy furniture · Warm amber rooms | Color palette and set design vocabulary. Warm surfaces, tactile materials, never clinical. |
| Vogue Italia · Jeweled hoops · Tinsel fringe · Glitter Superman | Fashion editorial posture. Even food photography should feel styled by someone with taste. |

## Photography Principles

1. **Motion first** — the drizzle mid-pour is always more compelling than the product at rest
2. **Warm surfaces** — wood, linen, ceramic, never stainless or marble
3. **Scale play** — oversized product, miniature world, or extreme macro are all on-brand
4. **Editorial styling** — everything should look like it was shot for a food magazine, not a grocery flyer
5. **No studio-white backgrounds** — the brand lives in real environments

